On huge neural networks these days, we train our model to overfit the training data . However, we still regularize neural networks through dropout.

Dropout -  inside the middle layers of the neural network, we throw away some inputs or make them zero, with a probability p. This prevents feature co-adaptation. This is also like ensemble training as you are training with different permutations of the same neural network.

Example:

Training time: at each instance of evaluation, randomly set 50% of the inputs to each neuron to 0

Test time: halve the model weights

No co-adaptation: a feature cannot only be useful in the presence of particular other features

Dropout is a feature dependent regularization

Using vector operations is much faster in python as compared to running a for loop

Parameter initialization  - use random numbers for this rather than 0 or any constant - this leads to symmetries - similar to having multiple copies of a single feature - if you are starting gradient descent from a symmetric point then the gradient doesn't know where to go

Optimizers - instead of hand tuning the learning rate with SGD, we can use adaptive optimizers that scale the adjustment to individual parameters by an accumulated gradient - essentially use the gradient of the parameter to decide how much you move

Adam is a good one but since word vectors are sparse, we use other optimizers

Language models

Predicting what word comes next or giving a probability distribution of what word comes next

N gram language model

N is the length of the word sequence that we are looking at before predicting what will come next

Unigram - if we look at probability of a single word

Bigram, trigram and so on

Markov assumption for n gram language models

X (t + 1) word depends on the preceding n - 1 words

Sparsity problems with n gram language models

What if a particular set of words in the test data never occurred in the training data, for example, if we predict, students opened their W and if W was never in the data then the probability would be zero. To solve this, we can add a small delta to the count of every word in the vocabulary. This is called smoothing.

Another sparsity problem is that if we have never seen the words students opened their in the data then we cannot calculate any probability for students opened their W

Partial solution - you reduce the context, so if you are in a n gram model, you look at the last n - 1 words instead of the last n words and keep reducing the context until you are able to calculate the probability once again

This leads to a problem, on one hand you need more context to better predict the next word on the other hand the sparsity problem leads to using less context to predict the next word

In practice, five gram models were the largest thing people dealt with.

Storage problem - you need to store the count for all the n-grams you saw in the corpus. Increasing n or increasing corpus increases the model size

Fixed window neural language model

A feedforward neural network used for language modeling where prediction of a word is based solely on a fixed size window of preceding context words.

The model takes as input the embeddings of a fxied number of preceding words

These embeddings are concatenated and processed through a neural network

The output is a probability distribution over the vocabulary for the next word computed using softmax

Better than n gram as it used fewer parameters, deals with sparsity problem and does not store probabilities for all observed n grams

However, the fixed window is limited context and enlarging the window increases the number of parameters

The fixed window model does not share weights across positions and cannot process sequences of arbitrary length, lacing the symmetry and efficiency of RNNs - in simple words, depending on where the input is, different weights are applied to it thus lacing symmetry

Recurrent neural networks

We take a word sequence, convert each word into its word embedding. Then we have an initial hidden state. This can be a vector filled with zeroes. We multiply this with a weight vector, add this to the product of a weight matrix and the word embedding of the first word. Moving to the next word, we take the previous hidden layer, again multiply it with a weight matrix and then add the product of the weight matrix and the word embedding. We do this for all the words and add a bias term and the whole thing goes through a non-linearity function which has been tanh historically.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

After this, we take the final hidden state, multiply that with a matrix, add a bias and put that through a softmax and then sample from that softmax.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

RNN advantages

Can process any length of input

Computation for step t can in theory use information from many steps back - the memory of previous context vanishes as we progress through words - in some sense this is right as more recent words are better indicators but - however, RNNs forget stuff very quickly

Model size does not increase for longer input context

Same weights applied on every timestep so there is symmetry -

Disadvantages

Recurrent computation is slow - one hidden vector at a time - like a for loop

Teacher forcing

A training technique where the model is guided by providing the ground truth output from the training data as input for each subsequent time step instead of relying on its own previous predications.

During training after the model makes a prediction at time step t, the actual target from the training dataset is fed as input at the next time step t + 1 rather than the output generated by the model itself.

This leads to faster convergence and reduced error propagation as mistakes made early in the sequence do not compound in later steps.

Limitations:

Exposure bias - the model becomes overly dependent on ground truth inputs during training which can lead to performance issues during inference when only its previous predictions are available.

To address this, techniques like scheduled sampling are sometimes used, gradually transitioning the model to use its own predictions during training

Instead of running the rnn over the whole corpus, which accumulates losses and hidden states for a billion words in the corpus, we cut our data into segments of a given length and then run our rnn on those segments and then compute the loss for each segment and update the parameters using the losses of each segment.

Segmenting the corpus into sentences means that each sentence becomes a separate sequence for the RNN to process.

Within each sentence: The RNN processes one word at a time in sequence, not as a batch/group to a single layer all at once.

For each word, the RNN takes the word (or its embedding) as input, updates its hidden state, and passes context along the sentence.

The hidden state is reset (often to zeros) at the start of each new sentence to prevent context from one sentence bleeding into another.

Summary:

You do not input the entire sentence at once to one layer.

Instead, you feed one word at a time sequentially to the RNN, so that the hidden state for each time step represents all prior words in that sentence only.

This lets your model learn sentence-level structure, avoiding one huge hidden state chain for the whole corpus.

 the weight vector (and all parameters) for the hidden layer in a standard RNN are the same at every time step.

The hidden-to-hidden weights, input-to-hidden weights, and biases are fixed (shared) across all words/steps in the sequence and all sentences.

Truncated Backpropagation Through Time (TBPTT): A common speed-up technique where backpropagation is run for a shorter number of time steps (e.g., 20) instead of the full segment length, even though the forward pass still updates the hidden state using the full context

When a parameter like wh (a weight matrix for hidden states) is used at multiple places in a network—such as in recurrent neural networks (RNNs) where weights are shared across timesteps—the partial derivative of the loss with respect to that weight is computed by summing the individual gradients from each occurrence where the parameter is used.

Generating with an RNN model

This process involves starting with an initial hidden state (often using a "start of sequence" symbol), generating a word, feeding that generated word back as the next input, and repeating this "roll-out" to create a sequence until an "end of sequence" symbol is produced

To get the initial word for word generation with an RNN, you typically feed a special "start of sequence" () symbol into the model

This symbol acts as a pseudo-word, having its own word embedding. The RNN processes this initial input and its corresponding hidden state is then used to predict the probability distribution over all possible first words. From this distribution, a first word is sampled (generated) to begin the sequence.

It's mentioned that RNNs can also be built to generate text character by character instead of word by word, which can be useful for things like generating words that look like English or specific types of names. Used in dna sequencing

Contextual RNNs: The hidden state can be initialized with external information, such as RGB values of a color, to guide the generation. An example of generating paint color names based on RGB values is shown, highlighting the model's ability to create plausible-sounding names
